They can be strong yes because really all a waterspout really is, is a tornado over the water lol. Now I'm putting my foot in my mouth. As a storm chaser who has been within a few hundred feet of a large tornado & a waterspout I'm likely one of the idiots here hehehe

# Russian fishermen film stunning waterspout -- “as the storm broke out, we tried to tether ourselves to a larger ship, but the ropes broke apart, and we had to unmoor from them and we collided, it was a miracle that we survived” https://www.rt.com/news/433540-whirlwind-tornado-black-sea/ … # tornado

The funnel cloud over New York Harbor wasn’t a waterspout (tornado over water) or an actual tornado. In this case, just a rotating cloud/storm — but these can become tornadoes/waterspouts with little or no warning, so be safe.

I got a question, why is it easier for a waterspout to form from a storm than it is for a tornado to form on land? Seems like we always see a lot of waterspouts spawned from storms offshore but not many tornados once it emerges onto land. I’ve always wondered why this is
